{"text": " Today's a big day, we're transplanting the soursoft tree to the new garden. A couple weeks ago, I started by root pruning this entire tree to make sure that it could grow some new roots closer in so that it would have a better chance of success when we go to transplant. And today's the big day, it's finally time to dig this thing up and move it to the new house. Fortunately, the roots on soursoft trees are pretty shallow, so it's easy to get underneath them and cut them free in order to be able to transplant the tree. Moving any tree this size is exhausting and a whole lot of work, but these typically move a lot easier than some other tropical fruit trees because they don't have very big roots. After I had the root ball free, I pruned the tree that way it would have less of a canopy to support while it transitions to its new home. Then I bagged up the roots and it's time to load this into the truck and take it to the new house. On the way there, I also covered it with a tarp that way it would protect it from any wind damage as well as sun damage on the drive. Back at my house, I dropped it into the ground, backfilled it with soil, and now I'm just giving it a nice deep watering and I'm going to continue to do this for the next couple weeks until it settles into its new home. To minimize the stress from transplanting, as well as the fact that it already has dropped a lot of leaves due to the cold snaps, I did give it some shade coverage and some wind protection. And to lock in extra moisture and nutrients, I added oak leaves around it, that way it would really be able to hold in the moisture. It'll be a couple weeks before we know for sure if this worked or not, but I'm pretty confident that it'll bounce back and be better than ever, but we'll just have to wait and see. Until next time, get outside and see what you can find.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.52, "text": " Today's a big day, we're transplanting the soursoft tree to 